<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-04-26T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-04-26T12:00:00-05:00" n="563" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d563">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">822.72 AL 5/39: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gade</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-04-26T12:00:00-05:00">April 26,
                                1938—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>38. General Enriquez<note n="52" xml:id="d563fn52">Provisional President
                                of Ecuador.</note> last night gave All America Cables an ultimatum
                            requiring payment of $354,000 as settlement of alleged back taxes. If
                            ultimatum which expires on Thursday is not accepted he <pb facs="0564" n="555" xml:id="pg_555"/> threatens to seize the Company’s
                            properties. Roosevelt,<note n="53" xml:id="d563fn53">John K.
                                Roosevelt.</note> the Vice President of the company, has requested
                            no action from the Legation but merely wishes to keep it informed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gade</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>